[div class=p 
	"This is a sister game to the original NES Castlevania that was released for the MSX2 at the same time.
	$LF
	"Unlike Castlevania, each stage requires you to find a white key to proceed to the next stage.
	$LF
	"The levels are different and often very non-linear and mazelike, frequently forcing you to find secrets to proceed.
	$LF
	"There's also a number of items strewn throughout the levels which you can pick up, which range from useless for the TAS to completely game-breaking.
	$LF
	"In this game, hearts act as both your subweapon ammo as well as currency to buy items from merchants with.
	$LF
	"This run needs quite a few hearts, which makes proper heart routing crucial for the run.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"This run uses a couple new major discoveries to save 3618 frames, or just over a minute, over the previous 2013 run.
	$LF
	"These new discoveries significantly change how the game is played.
	$LF
	"More detail is outlined in the comments below.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=TasingProcess 
	" TASing Process
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"openMSX normally relies on a rewind-based system, where the emulator is configured by default to go back 1 frame if you hit Scroll Lock, and 60 frames if you hit PageUp, which I used in the past.
	$LF
	"For this TAS, I tried to emulate how typical emulators like BizHawk work, and bound loading and saving of different replay slots to the F1 - F8 keys (which in turn necessitated moving the F1 and F2 keys, which are used by the game, to somewhere else).
	$LF
	"This was hugely beneficial for TASing, as having the ability to easily and quickly jump to a precise moment in time is massively helpful.
	$LF
	"This allowed for a lot more precision in making the TAS, which is something I felt I was missing before.
	$LF
	"In particular, it made the process of the finding the first (or last) frame where an action is possible significantly easier, which was particularly troublesome before.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"One downside to this however is that the rerecord count is not accurate, since all saveloads are discarded.
	$LF
	"I do not have an estimate for the real rerecord count.
	$LF
	"Going purely by the amount of time spent on the TAS however, I spent about 2 - 3 weeks on routing, and another 3 weeks on the actual TAS, so make of that what you will.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Like a lot of MSX games, the game generally runs at 30 FPS and will only accept input every other frame.
	$LF
	"For the most part, you can just get by with making sure to hold every button for two frames, and getting used to pushing Frame Advance twice each time.
	$LF
	"Sometimes, when the game is busy, you might need to hold a key for two or even more frames in a row to get the game to register it.
	$LF
	"Sometimes, it might also require holding unrelated buttons at the same time.
	$LF
	"I do not quite know why that is.
	$LF
	"This also means that Simon only ever moves by 2 pixels at a time.
	$LF
	"This can sometimes be a problem when precise positioning is important.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Unlike the previous runs, this TAS was done almost entirely on the MSX joystick rather than the keyboard.
	$LF
	"The primary advantage of this is that you can hold Up on the joystick without Simon attempting to jump, which makes climbing up stairs significantly less problematic.
	$LF
	"The keyboard was however still used heavily for luck manipulation.
	$LF
	"Playing on joystick still doesn't fix some of the game's other strange controls, such as using subweapons with the directional inputs.
	$LF
	"You're stuck with that.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=StairGlitch 
	" Stair Glitch
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"The stair glitch was discovered by AgentWyvern at the beginning of 2023.
	$LF
	"By walking on a staircase for exactly 32 steps, or 512 frames, you can walk beyond the intended end of a staircase and keep going.
	$LF
	"The reason for this is a counter in RAM that keeps track of how many frames Simon has walked on a staircase for.
	$LF
	"It is located at address 0xC42B.
	$LF
	"When the counter rolls over to 0 as you hit the final step of the staircase, the game will not realize that Simon is supposed to exit the staircase.
	$LF
	"I am not sure why the programmers decided they needed that counter, I haven't messed enough with Z80 assembly to find out.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Once the stair glitch is active, you can keep going until you hit another solid floor.
	$LF
	"When you hit a vertical screen edge, it depends on the room what happens.
	$LF
	"If there is a valid screen transition defined for the ceiling or the floor of the room, you can walk into the next room as normal.
	$LF
	"If there is no screen transition defined for the bottom of the screen, Simon will die as if he fell into a bottomless pit.
	$LF
	"If there is no screen transition for the ceiling, Simon will also lose a life, but then respawn in the same room without any of his items.
	$LF
	"In a similar way, hitting a horizontal screen edge will send Simon into the next room when a screen transition is active, otherwise, Simon will simply wrap around the current room.
	$LF
	"Because of this, stair glitches are not always usable where it seems like they should be possible.
	$LF
	"It is also in theory possible to chain several stair glitches to go through multiple floors, but no applications have been found for this.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"You cannot carry a stair glitch through a vertical screen transition, as Simon's Y position will be offset from 1 pixel from where it should be when you go through a screen edge, which causes the stair glitch to fail once you attempt it.
	$LF
	"Because of this, you must set up a stair glitch on the same screen that you use it on, which limits some of the applications.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Despite these limitations and the long setup time, it is still possible to perform a number of major shortcuts using the glitch, as the level design often forces you to backtrack for agonizingly long distances otherwise.
	$LF
	"All applications are noted below in the stage-by-stage comments.
	$LF
	"This glitch is ultimately the reason why I wanted to redo the run.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=StopwatchGlitch 
	" Stopwatch Glitch
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"This glitch goes back to at least Jaguar King's 2014 SDA run of the game.
	$LF
	"Put simply, if you exit a stage while the stopwatch is active, the stopwatch will remain active indefinitely.
	$LF
	"This can be done either by letting a boss orb time out after beating a level, or by immediately using 
	$LF
	"the stopwatch before entering a door, although the second option is much faster.
	$LF
	"All enemies are frozen permanently then.
	$LF
	"If you beat a level, time will remain frozen until you find another stopwatch and use it again.
	$LF
	"Dying resets the stopwatch glitch.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"This glitch has huge application for real-time speedruns, as it makes the game much more bearable than it would be otherwise.
	$LF
	"It however comes with some serious downsides for the TAS, as it both locks you out of some damage boosts that would be possible otherwise, and also results in a much more boring TAS, as you basically end up just leisurely strolling throughout all the levels without any of the enemies bothering you.
	$LF
	"Despite this, some enemies are still placed in inconvenient locations, which means you're still forced to deal with them somehow.
	$LF
	"Due to this, I initially passed the glitch up and didn't give it much mind until I started this TAS.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"For this TAS, I actually went and did a proper route test first to see if the stopwatch glitch was actually faster or not.
	$LF
	"Ultimately it turns out that the stopwatch glitch ends up saving time due to a number of different reasons.
	$LF
	"In total, it comes out to saving between 10 - 13 seconds, which is why I decided I wanted to include it for this TAS.
	$LF
	"One unexpected benefit the stopwatch glitch provides is lag: the game just has so much less slowdown when the enemies aren't flailing about constantly.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"The most convenient place to grab a stopwatch is fairly early on, in Stage 4. 
	$LF
	"Once you exit the level though, there is no convenient place to grab a stopwatch in Level 3 and 5, and no stopwatch whatsoever in Level 4.
	$LF
	"This means that when you carry the stopwatch glitch out of Level 2, you're basically locked into it until the endgame.
	$LF
	"This ends up creating two radically different routes throughout the game, one where the game plays as normal, and one where time is frozen, which, as mentioned, basically turns the game into a sightseeing tour.
	$LF
	"It might seem lame that none of the enemies actually pose a challenge to me, but ultimately the timesave was just too large for me to leave on the table.
	$LF
	"The stopwatch glitch also introduces some unexpected new perks that are highlighted in the stage-by-stage comments below.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Speaking of...
	$LF
]div
